-- The 200 pairs were constructed using option (d) "pairs of choice" from the project spec, anchored to the 200 films from my personal ranking task. For each base movie I knew well, I generated recommendations along five similarity axes: (1) same director, (2) same franchise / direct sequel, (3) same lead actor, (4) shared genre + era, and (5) thematic or stylistic kinship (e.g., heist comedies, mind-benders, WW2 dramas).
-- The 100 reasonable-but-bad pairs (ratings 1-5) are inspired by option (a) "false positives of interest": films that share an obvious surface trait (same actor, same director, same franchise, same genre) but diverge sharply on a second axis — tone, audience, quality, or scale. Examples include same-actor pairs with opposite registers (Hanks in Forrest Gump → Saving Private Ryan), franchise quality drops (Goldfinger → Die Another Day), and same-genre tonal mismatches (Independence Day → Blade Runner). Every such justification follows the spec template: "Though both movies are A, it is a bad recommendation since B."
